Reporting of events through aggregate social media has become increasingly important.
Recent crises have highlighted this trend, with the extensive use of Twitter and Reddit for news and crowdsour\
cing in the Boston Marathon bombings of April 2013.
Building on the text partitioner of Williams et. al. \cite{williams-partitioner}, we develop a method of findi\
ng and classifying stories in real time text.
This ``storyfinder'' computes entropy and ambient valence of phrases, then shifts these measures on individual\
 phrases over time to detect which stories are driving significant changes in langauge use \cite{desu-ambient}\
.
An attempt to implement this method on Twitter during the week of the 2013 Boston Marathon serves as a case st\
udy on the effectiveness of this method.
With access to the real-time Twitter feed, this measure can hopefully be fully tested and built into a useful \
distributed news finder.
